;; Book of Arcade Games — Chapter 8: Tile Worlds

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(chapter
  :book                "Book of Arcade Games"
  :chapter-number      8
  :title               "Tile Worlds"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :G
  :author-lane         "arcade-games-engineer-lane-2026-07-16"
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :voice               "sakura-teaching + game-design"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :draws-from-preserved (:book "book-of-games-preserved" :ch 14)
  :prose
"So far every game has fit on one screen. Chapter 8 breaks out of the
box. A tile world is a grid of small squares — ground, wall, sky —
laid across a canvas larger than the display. The camera pans; the
player walks; the world unfolds under their character's feet.

Tile worlds are how a small computer punches above its weight. Instead
of storing pixels for every part of the map, you store one small
sprite per TYPE of tile and paint them in a grid. A 40x15 map of 32x32
tiles is 600 tiles, which is 1200 bytes of tile-index data, and paints
a 1280x480 pixel world.

This chapter lays out a tile world, walks a character across it, sets
camera bounds so the view stays inside the map, and lets the kid TYPE
a level as a string list and see it come alive. The last part is what
turns 'a game' into 'a game the kid made.'

---

## 8.1 The tile grid

The simplest possible tile world: a ground row.

```scheme
;; A 40-tile-wide ground row across the bottom of a larger world.
(define (ground-row)
  (world/reset!)
  ;; scene/grid 'ground columns rows cell-w cell-h origin-x origin-y
  (scene/grid 'ground 40 1 32 32 0 200)
  (world/each 'ground
              (lambda (t)
                (entity/shape! t 'rect 32 32)
                (entity/solid! t #t)))
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 100 168)))
    (entity/shape! p 'rect 16 32)
    (entity/solid! p #t)
    (entity/gravity-scale! p 1)
    (world/gravity! 0 0.5)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p -3 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p 3 0))
       (when (input/pressed? 'a)
         (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p)) -10))
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (world/each 'ground
                   (lambda (t)
                     (paint-cell 'ground (entity/x t) (entity/y t) 32 32)))
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 16 32)))))

(big-bang ground-row)
```

`scene/grid 'ground 40 1 32 32 0 200` says: spawn a grid tagged
'ground, 40 columns × 1 row, tile size 32×32, top-left origin at
(0, 200). Result: 40 tiles side by side at y=200. Each is a real
entity you can query and manipulate.

We iterate the tiles once at setup with `world/each` and mark each
solid. The physics engine now includes them in collision resolution.
The player, also solid, cannot pass through.

The player can walk left and right along the ground and jump. But
they can only see the leftmost 320 pixels of the 1280-pixel world.
Camera time.

---

## 8.2 Camera follow

Move the camera as the player moves.

```scheme
;; The camera follows the player. Now walking right REVEALS the world.
(define (scrolling-world)
  (world/reset!)
  (scene/grid 'ground 40 1 32 32 0 200)
  (world/each 'ground
              (lambda (t) (entity/shape! t 'rect 32 32) (entity/solid! t #t)))
  ;; Add a few 'wall towers.
  (world/spawn 'wall 400 168)
  (world/spawn 'wall 400 136)
  (world/spawn 'wall 700 168)
  (world/spawn 'wall 700 136)
  (world/spawn 'wall 700 104)
  (world/each 'wall
              (lambda (t) (entity/shape! t 'rect 32 32) (entity/solid! t #t)))
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 100 168)))
    (entity/shape! p 'rect 16 32)
    (entity/solid! p #t)
    (world/gravity! 0 0.5)
    (world/camera-follow! p 0.1 60 40)     ;; smooth follow, 60x40 dead
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p -3 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p 3 0))
       (when (input/pressed? 'a)
         (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p)) -10))
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (world/each 'ground
                   (lambda (t)
                     (paint-cell 'ground (entity/x t) (entity/y t) 32 32)))
       (world/each 'wall
                   (lambda (t)
                     (paint-cell 'wall (entity/x t) (entity/y t) 32 32)))
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 16 32)))))

(big-bang scrolling-world)
```

`world/camera-follow! p 0.1 60 40` says: follow entity `p` with lag
factor 0.1 (10% of the way each frame — smooth), only re-centering
when the player leaves a 60×40 pixel deadzone. Walk right, the world
slides left under you. Walk back, it slides right.

The paint calls did not change. `paint-cell` takes world coordinates,
and the runtime subtracts the camera position before drawing. The kid
does not have to think about screen-vs-world coordinates — the engine
handles it.

---

## 8.3 Camera bounds

The camera should not scroll past the edge of the world.

```scheme
;; Constrain the camera to a rectangle so you never see 'outside'.
(define (bounded-world)
  (world/reset!)
  (scene/grid 'ground 40 1 32 32 0 200)
  (world/each 'ground
              (lambda (t) (entity/shape! t 'rect 32 32) (entity/solid! t #t)))
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 100 168)))
    (entity/shape! p 'rect 16 32)
    (entity/solid! p #t)
    (world/gravity! 0 0.5)
    (world/camera-follow! p 0.1 60 40)
    ;; World is 40 tiles wide (1280 px) tall enough for jumps up to y=0.
    (world/camera-bounds! 0 0 1280 480)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p -3 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p 3 0))
       (when (input/pressed? 'a)
         (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p)) -10))
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (world/each 'ground
                   (lambda (t)
                     (paint-cell 'ground (entity/x t) (entity/y t) 32 32)))
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 16 32)))))

(big-bang bounded-world)
```

At the left edge, camera stops even as the player walks further left
(they leave the deadzone). At the right edge, camera stops. This is
the standard sidescroller camera. It costs one line of code
(`world/camera-bounds!`).

---

## 8.4 Levels as strings

The powerful part: type your level as a string of characters, one
character per tile. Parse it into entities.

```scheme
;; A little level design language.
;;   #  ground/wall
;;   .  air (nothing)
;;   P  player start
;;   G  goal

(define level-1
  '(\"..............................\"
    \"..............................\"
    \"..............................\"
    \"..............................\"
    \"..............#####...........\"
    \"..............................\"
    \"........########..............\"
    \"..............................\"
    \"...##...................######\"
    \"..............................\"
    \"P........................#...G\"
    \"##############################\"))

(define (parse-level lines)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((rows (length lines))
        (player-spawn #f)
        (goal-spawn #f))
    (let loop-r ((row 0))
      (when (< row rows)
        (let ((line (list-ref lines row)))
          (let loop-c ((col 0))
            (when (< col (string-length line))
              (let ((ch (string-ref line col))
                    (x (* col 32))
                    (y (* row 20)))
                (cond
                  ((char=? ch #\\#)
                   (let ((t (world/spawn 'ground x y)))
                     (entity/shape! t 'rect 32 20)
                     (entity/solid! t #t)))
                  ((char=? ch #\\P)
                   (set! player-spawn (list x y)))
                  ((char=? ch #\\G)
                   (set! goal-spawn (list x y))))
                (loop-c (+ col 1)))))
          (loop-r (+ row 1)))))
    (list player-spawn goal-spawn)))

(define (play-level)
  (let* ((spawns (parse-level level-1))
         (player-spawn (car spawns))
         (goal-spawn   (cadr spawns))
         (p (world/spawn 'player (car player-spawn) (cadr player-spawn))))
    (when goal-spawn
      (let ((g (world/spawn 'goal (car goal-spawn) (cadr goal-spawn))))
        (entity/shape! g 'rect 20 20)
        (entity/sensor! g #t)))
    (entity/shape! p 'rect 16 20)
    (entity/solid! p #t)
    (world/gravity! 0 0.5)
    (world/camera-follow! p 0.1 60 40)
    (world/camera-bounds! 0 0 960 240)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p -3 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p 3 0))
       (when (input/pressed? 'a)
         (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p)) -8))
       (world/step)
       ;; Check goal collision.
       (for-each
        (lambda (pair)
          (let ((a (car pair)) (b (cadr pair)))
            (when (or (and (eq? (entity/kind a) 'player)
                           (eq? (entity/kind b) 'goal))
                      (and (eq? (entity/kind b) 'player)
                           (eq? (entity/kind a) 'goal)))
              (paint-text \"YOU WIN!\" 120 100))))
        (world/collisions))
       (paint-clear)
       (world/each 'ground
                   (lambda (t)
                     (paint-cell 'ground (entity/x t) (entity/y t) 32 20)))
       (world/each 'goal
                   (lambda (g)
                     (paint-cell 'goal (entity/x g) (entity/y g) 20 20)))
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 16 20)))))

(big-bang play-level)
```

Read the level string. It looks like a picture of the level. That is
the point. The kid can literally SEE the world in the source. Change
a `.` to a `#` and a wall appears. Move `P` to change spawn. Move `G`
to change goal. That IS level design, no editor needed.

`char=?` compares characters. `#\\#` is Scheme's character literal for
'#'. `string-ref` indexes into a string. `list-ref` indexes into a
list. These are R7RS standards; every Motoi runtime has them.

---

## 8.5 A level to walk

Ten sample levels live in Appendix J (ASCII-to-Tile Level Format).
Here is a tiny one you can play right now — copy the string list, save
the file, run it.

```
'(\"........................\"
  \"........................\"
  \"...#####................\"
  \"........................\"
  \"........................\"
  \"...............#####....\"
  \"........................\"
  \"........#####...........\"
  \"........................\"
  \"P.......................G\"
  \"########################\")
```

Eleven lines, twenty-four columns. Three floating platforms, a ground
row, a spawn, a goal. Playable in fifteen seconds.

Appendix J has ten more like this — some tricky, some breezy, all
runnable with the parser above.

---

## 8.6 The four patterns in a tile world

**Composition.** A world is composed of tiles. A tile is composed of
shape and solid. A level is composed of tiles arranged by the parser
from a string. Composition happens at three scales: tile, world, game.

**Orchestration.** The frame loop orchestrates: input, physics, tile
paint, entity paint. Tiles are stationary; you could paint them once
to a background buffer and skip re-painting each frame. Optimization
for later.

**In-routing.** Input routes to player movement. The level string
routes to entity spawns via the parser — a static in-routing, done
once at level load. `world/collisions` routes goal-touches to a
win-check.

**Routing.** Paint calls route to the framebuffer, adjusted by the
camera position under the hood. `world/camera-follow!` routes the
player's position to the camera every frame. Tile-load routes strings
to entities.

---

## 8.7 Common desktop tasks

**Shop-as-map.** A shop with lots of product categories can be
represented as a small tile world: each category is a room, walls
between them, doors to open. The kid navigates by walking rather than
clicking. Not for every shop, but for the whimsical ones.

**Save-navigation game.** After a shop sale ends, run a small
'find-your-favorite' minigame: your last three viewed items are goals
at scattered positions; you navigate a tile world to touch them all.
Completion = a bonus coupon.

---

## 8.8 Pitfalls

**Player sinks into the floor.** Your tile shape doesn't match the
grid cell size. Tile is 32×32; you set `entity/shape! t 'rect 32 20`.
Fix: match the shape to the visual.

**Camera stops before the player reaches an edge.** Your camera
bounds are too tight. `world/camera-bounds! 0 0 world-w world-h`
should use the FULL world dimensions.

**Level appears offset.** Your parser uses `(* col 32)` but you spawn
tiles at `y = (* row 20)` — mismatched tile size in x vs y. Use the
same number.

**One giant tile row.** Your loop broke early. Check the `loop-c`
termination condition — you want `<`, not `<=` (or `string-length` +
1, off by one).

**Player warps to spawn but never falls.** Player spawned INSIDE a
tile; the physics resolves by pushing them out (probably up) instantly.
Spawn one tile-row above ground.

---

## 8.9 Try this yourself

1. Add a `C` character for coin. Parse into a sensor entity. Collect
   on touch. Score in a counter.
2. Add a `E` character for enemy. Parse into an entity that patrols
   left-right on its row.
3. Add a `S` character for spring. Parse into an entity that on
   player-contact sets player vy to -14 (super-jump).
4. Write your own level. Save it as `my-level.slat` in the same
   directory. Load it in the parser.
5. Add a scrolling background parallax layer (chapter 9 will make
   this beautiful).
6. Add a level-select screen: three levels; arrow to pick; 'a' to
   play; on win, back to select.

---

## 8.10 What we built

`scene/grid` for cheap grid-generated worlds. `world/camera-follow!`
+ `world/camera-bounds!` for scrolling. A string-based level format
that a kid can read and write. A goal sensor. Ten sample levels in
Appendix J.

Next chapter: three layers of scrolling background, each at a
different rate. The world gains depth without gaining a Z-axis.")

